<h2>1. Butterflies</h2>

<p>During March and April the butterflies start to emerge. The ones I most often see, due to their bright, almost luminous wings, are the cabbage whites or small whites. There are also red admirals, mostly browny-black with two orangey-red stripes on their wings, and white spots. There’s the small tortoiseshell, which is almost completely orangey-red, with black and white edges, and black and yellow stripes. And the peacock butterflies, also orangey-red, with their recognisable eyespots.</p>

<p>Since I live in a city where most of the landscape is brick and concrete, I don’t often get to see butterflies as they live mostly by wildflowers and particular plants. If you have a garden growing certain plants can attract them to your garden. Otherwise the best places can be in the countryside or botanical gardens.</p>


